Account databases — passwd, shadow, and group.

All of that identity data lives in three plain-text files under slash-etc. Learn their fields, and most of user management just demystifies itself.

The first is etc-passwd, the user list. It's world-readable, one line per user, and each line has seven colon-separated fields. In order: the username; a password placeholder, which today is always just the letter x; the UID; the primary GID; the GECOS field, which is the full name or a comment; the home directory; and finally the login shell. That last field is a handy lever: set someone's shell to slash-usr-sbin-nologin and they simply can't log in, which is the standard move for system accounts. And notice: the actual password hash is not in this file. Anyone on the system can read etc-passwd, which is fine, because there's nothing secret in it.

So where's the hash? That's the second file, etc-shadow. It holds the hashed passwords, and unlike passwd, it's readable only by root, with permissions six-four-zero, owned by root and the shadow group. That's literally why it's called "shadow": it shadows the secret half out of the world-readable passwd file. Besides the hash, shadow holds the password-aging fields: when the password was last changed, its minimum and maximum age, the warning window, and the expiry date. The password field can also carry special values: an exclamation mark means the account is locked; an asterisk means it never had a password, typical for system accounts; and an empty field means no password at all, which is a security disaster you should never allow. The hash itself starts with a marker for its algorithm: dollar-six is SHA-512, dollar-y is the modern yescrypt.

The third file is etc-group, which lists groups and their members, with four fields: the group name, a placeholder, the GID, and a comma-separated list of members. Remember the distinction: your primary group comes from field four of passwd, while the supplementary groups you belong to are listed here in group. Some common ones to recognize: sudo, or wheel on Red Hat systems, whose members may run sudo; adm, for reading system logs; and docker, whose members are effectively root, so be careful who you add.

One last, important habit: in scripts, don't grep these files directly. Use getent instead, getent passwd alice, or getent group sudo. getent consults every configured source, including network directories like LDAP, not just the local files, so your script keeps working in real environments.
